<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="About-This-Analysis">About This Analysis<a class="anchor-link" href="#About-This-Analysis"> </a></h1><p>This analysis was done by <a href="https://twitter.com/joeyrichar">Joseph Richards</a></p>
<p>In this project<sup class="footnote-ref" id="fnref-3"><a href="#fn-3">1</a></sup>, we attempt to estimate the true mortality rate<sup class="footnote-ref" id="fnref-1"><a href="#fn-1">2</a></sup> for COVID-19 while controlling for country-level covariates<sup class="footnote-ref" id="fnref-2"><a href="#fn-2">3</a></sup><sup class="footnote-ref" id="fnref-4"><a href="#fn-4">4</a></sup> such as:</p>
<ul>
<li>age of outbreak in the country</li>
<li>transparency of the country's government</li>
<li>access to healthcare</li>
<li>demographics such as age of population and rural vs. urban</li>
</ul>
<p>Estimating a mortality rate lower than the overall reported rate likely implies that there has been <strong>significant under-testing and under-reporting of cases globally</strong>.</p>
<h2 id="Interpretation-of-Country-Level-Parameters">Interpretation of Country-Level Parameters<a class="anchor-link" href="#Interpretation-of-Country-Level-Parameters"> </a></h2><ol>
<li>days_since_first_case - positive (very statistically significant).  As time since outbreak increases, expected mortality rate <strong>increases</strong>, as expected.</li>
<li>cpi - negative (statistically significant).  As government transparency increases, expected mortality rate <strong>decreases</strong>.  This may mean that less transparent governments under-report cases, hence inflating the mortality rate.</li>
<li>healthcare avg. out-of-pocket spending - no significant trend.</li>
<li>hospital beds per capita - no significant trend.</li>
<li>Human Capital Index - no significant trend (slightly negative = mortality rates decrease with increased mobilization of the country)</li>
<li>percent over 65 - positive (statistically significant).  As population age increases, the mortality rate also <strong>increases</strong>, as expected.</li>
<li>percent rural - no significant trend.</li>
</ol>
<div class="footnotes">
<hr>
<ol><li id="fn-3"><p>Full details about the model are available at:  <a href="https://github.com/jwrichar/COVID19-mortality">https://github.com/jwrichar/COVID19-mortality</a><a href="#fnref-3" class="footnote">&#8617;</a></p></li>
<li id="fn-1"><p>As of March 10, the <strong>overall reported mortality rate is 3.5%</strong>.  However, this figure does not account for <strong>systematic biases in case reporting and testing</strong>.  The observed mortality of COVID-19 has varied widely from country to country (as of early March 2020).  For instance, as of March 10, mortality rates have ranged from &lt; 0.1% in places like Germany (1100+ cases) to upwards of 5% in Italy (9000+ cases) and 3.9% in China (80k+ cases).<a href="#fnref-1" class="footnote">&#8617;</a></p></li>
<li id="fn-2"><p>The point of our modelling work here is to <strong>try to understand and correct for the country-to-country differences that may cause the observed discrepancies in COVID-19 country-wide mortality rates</strong>.  That way we can "undo" those biases and try to <strong>pin down an overall <em>real</em> mortality rate</strong>.<a href="#fnref-2" class="footnote">&#8617;</a></p></li>
<li id="fn-4"><p>The affects of these parameters are subject to change as more data are collected.<a href="#fnref-4" class="footnote">&#8617;</a></p></li>
</ol>
</div>

</div>
</div>
</div>
